column1: 227121;instagram;2018-11-15 07:13:35;FALSE;"i've watched the qspiracy since the start.
steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?
abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the bombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa me
column2: a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

column1: the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagate‚Ñ¢ was testing for the 2016 election.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the content and more or less fake accounts - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking the responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole thing is build on the same user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

column1: my attorney contacted the state prosecutor to inquire about the results of my rape kit
column2: which have been so delayed due to the detective's mistake of not informing the forensic lab or my identity so it could be entered into the line for testing.

column1: i was informed today that the detective assigned to my case submitted a warrant for my rapist's arrest in early october. however
column2: the prosecutors office requested further information and asked the detective to conduct a follow up interview with me two months ago and the detective simply never contacted me again despite being ordered to by the prosecutor. if he truly wanted my rapist in jail and this case to be prosecuted you would think he would want to the interview me and get the information he needed as soon as possible. this is just one of many attempts by this detective to sabotage the adjudication of my case. in response as to why he never contacted me despite being ordered to he said he has been ""busy with other cases."" he is a university police officer. what caliber of other cases is he so busy with that in 2 months he has had no time to ask me some follow up questions. for how long is the university and the state going to accept his clear lack of caring for the outcome of this case? mind you
column3: i wouldn't know any of this information had i not called about my rape kit that has been sitting untested for a year.

column1: now my attorney is trying to speak to the chief of police about why no one has contacted me for a follow up interview. i am just terrified of what the prosecutor needs to know in order to sign the warrant and if i will be able to answer those questions. also the thought of giving another complete statement is retraumatizing and terrifying.
can't just one thing go right? can't just one person treat me with dignity and provide me the information i am owed? can't just one person in a position of power do their job?

i am exhausted.";;en;;;;;;0;;rapesurvivorsupport;Survivors of Sexual Assault;;0;False;30;0;0;158;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/a561e58f6c3f811af6ff0f9977742850/5D146D64/t51.2885-15/e35/44600312_605909429826395_8694363871867406753_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"major update on my case:

column1: 227287;instagram;2018-11-15 04:00:32;FALSE;"i‚Äôm sitting in this hotel room trying to figure out which way this whole thing is going to turn out. i am a planner. i want to know what the ‚Äúnext step‚Äù is. where am i going? should i even be considering this. what happens if i lay it all out and people just nod and walk away uncomfortable. or worse
column2: try to put a heavy awkward empathetic hand on my shoulder as they tilt their head slightly
column4: take a deep breath and just sigh through their nose. ugh. that sigh. its the obvious sign to me that i have accidentally overshared again. wait
column5: it wasn‚Äôt really an accident. you were standing near by
column6: something happened that reminded me of that one time
column7: so you are welcome for the story. the story that shapes me. the story that sends others realing into disbelief that that could happen. here? to you? him!? shame is a funny thing. the hot humiliation that floods over me after i realize my story has made this other human uncomfortable. why are you uncomfortable? is it because you too have experienced something similar? is it because you think your story doesn‚Äôt affect you so you find no reason to ‚Äòbring it up.‚Äô ‚Äúhe doesn‚Äôt hold power of me!‚Äù ‚Äúit doesn‚Äôt even bother me anymore‚Äù the breakthroughs that i have accomplished over the past 15 years are incredible. but when i see someone who looks like him
column8: my body is overwhelmed with a fear that is irrational. you know that feeling when you see a cop while driving on the road? you aren‚Äôt even doing anything wrong! yet you flood with fear of being caught. exposed.

column1: fear is a liar. i am here to bring shame to the real lie. expose all that is holding us back from true healing.
you can be free. what are some lies that you are told or believe about your story?

column1: 227478;instagram;2018-11-14 23:57:31;FALSE;"it‚Äôs trans awareness week ‚Äî a time to raise the visibility of trans and gender non-conforming folks and the issues communities face (which tbh we should do all the time). trans justice
column3: and rights are reproductive justice. just some of the ways they intersect: - trans and gnc folks need sensitive
column5: and accessible reproductive care. remember: restrictions on reproductive freedom affect vulnerable communities *the most.*

column1: - trans and gnc rights are about bodily autonomy
- anti-choice legislators are very often the same people trying to restrict equality for trans and queer folks

column2: with some examples and anecdotes described by three different women
column3: we‚Äôre able to arrive at a fuller picture of why women are angry
column5: and how they can channel it and are channeling it in constructive ways. chemaly‚Äôs book is a bit more academic than traister‚Äôs. she references many studies and is more interested in the psychology of anger and how so much develops in the childhood and upbringing of girls. chemaly shares stories from her own life
column6: and the ones about parenting her daughter are especially poignant because you get a real sense that the way we treat boys and girls differently is a hard thing to overcome - it is so deeply engrained that even someone who has spent so much of her life studying this disparity and its deleterious effects on women and society can still fall into its traps. i‚Äôm glad chemaly wrote rage becomes her and i‚Äôm glad i read it. #goodreads #reading #igreads #bookstagram #bookstagrammer #instabooks #instabook #igbook #igbookreview #igbooks #igreaders #read #book #books #womensmarch #anger #women #feminism #igfeminist #activism #metoo #pinkwave;;en;#RageBecomesHer

i have something personal to share... this year has felt like a particularly hard year to be a woman to me. so many people i knew were sharing their stories online of sexual assault and abuse
column2: and i found myself shying away from social media. it hurt to read yet another story of harassment or abuse.  what's sad is that i wasn't shocked by it
column3: i was just worn down. and yet through this breaking open
column4: a quiet solidarity formed; a holding of space for people to share their stories. a community was being born. this roaring back of survivors saying

column1: sexual abuse and assault are happening to women
column3: and gender non-conforming people all over the world. it does not discriminate by ethnicity
column5: or political affiliation. this is a human issue. a little over a month ago i watched dr. christine blasey-ford's testimony along with the rest of the country. i don't know her. i don't know her alleged attacker. i wasn't there. but her story sounded very familiar to me. i recognized the quiver in her voice. i was sick to my stomach. and i couldn't sleep. i finally got up in the middle of the night
column6: sat at the piano and put my feelings on paper. afterwards i felt better and went to bed at peace. the next day i went in studio with my dear friend @jameyjaz and recorded what i had written
column7: which turned out to be this song.

column1: 227577;instagram;2018-11-14 20:54:16;FALSE;"this instagram community was once my safety
column2: full of people i knew would  stand up for me and defend  me from injustice. the truth settles like sediment in the river. i am so alone. left to wander through my past incandescent traumas
column3: they light up my past like candles on a birthday cake. my future is uncertain. hopefully there is more support in my future. i am left to navigate severe isolation and grief with an autistic nervous system that needs to rest so badly. it needs friendship
column4: and love. i need someone i can trust...and time and time again when i allow myself to step outside of the barrier that tells me i am not  safe with humans
column5: my trust gets shattered into a million pieces. it is not like glass
column6: we cannot recycle my trust into a new one. my trust
column7: and my healing are like diamonds. an immense commitment and amount of work is needed to forge even a single thread of it. the betrayals i face now are only purifying my ability to forge trust in myself
column8: but they come at an extreme cost. my friendship is pure like my heart
column9: and if you are so lucky to be in a position where i consider you my friend
column10: please realize that your actions have consequences. trauma has implications that you may not understand. the whole of my being carries implications you will never understand. i am ostracized
column11: and alone. my heart is heavy and one day i will walk into the river and let it sink and carry us all down the river.

column1: 227583;instagram;2018-11-14 20:59:20;FALSE;"today is hard. a 17 year old girls thong was held up in court as evidence that she was asking for it.

i can't help but imagine if i ever brought my attackers too court how they would treat me. would the bring up my past sexual history? would they wave the underwear around and scream that i was asking for it? would the people who destroyed my life walk away laughing while everyone shuns me as a slut.
it's times like this i find it impossible not to use
column2: picking up feels like the only way i can block out the pain and i'm angry that i can't. i want to drown out the agony in my head any way possible and i'm not and that hurts.

column1: i want the floor to open up and swallow me. my head keeps running in circles telling me to overdose and end the pain forever.

column2: i've called others in recovery and i've got some advice and i'm going to my best to have a shower
column3: clean up a little and mediate.

column2: but i have to shake myself. be grateful that i have a life
column3: that i have the ablity too feel things again. that i'm learning day by day how to deal with things sober.

column1: 227591;instagram;2018-11-14 21:07:06;FALSE;a poem written by a victim.;;en;;;;;;0;;thehidden.voices;Hidden Voices;;0;False;1;0;0;32;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/1ac36b31d4bcae531bfaf02698521dfb/5D257DAB/t51.2885-15/e35/44749280_514210962394471_2245515671088900600_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;a poem written by a victim.;a poem written by a victim.;poem written victim . ;[('poem'
the knowledge learned in treatment is so applicable to my career
column2: today i was speaking about tax technology and urged them to remember that perfection is the enemy of progress and that we can't wait for the tax software applications to be perfect before attempting to use them because perfection does not exist in software

column3: is inherently unmanageable. we have no control over the laws and reforms that are passed and must constantly adapt to change and be flexible with the solutions used. people get stuck in various habits at work and are hesitant to change because they want perfect software and will let small functionally issues prevent them from moving forward . this holds them back and eventually their skill set will be outdated and they will break their excel models and potentially pay penalties

column1: in all areas of life we must recognize that there will never be a perfect time to change and it will always be hard. but we can change proactively
column2: effectively and with intention rather than wait for things to fall apart and then we are forced to change under stress. i am proud of myself for listening to my own advice and implementing soberity with intention and focus! it's so crazy how similar the topic of tax technology and addiction treatment are. we are often scared of starting sobriety because we don't think we can be do it. keep trying
column3: keep going even when it's hard and seems impossible. each attempt is progress
column4: each relapse we learn more and more and eventually we change. keep going üí™

column1: my heart beats to a drum of authenticity
these are not traits that can be achieved through thought-out words or clever quotes alone. if we desire to achieve them
column2: we must breathe these on a regular basis and work hard to become them.

column1: to those small minded individuals who think that they can shame
column2: intimidate and/or bully me with my own history... you clearly misunderstand me and my message! üòÇüòò- so

column1: i own my story! i compete with no one but myself. i do not keep any skeletons in my closet
column2: because i live my truth! i have danced with too many of my own demons to be intimidated by you or yours. .

column1: i am evolving and growing every moment of every day- to me

column2: i found solace in poetry and the performing arts. as a survivor of child sex trafficking at the tender age of 7
column3: my experience felt unspeakable. it is difficult to remember a time before the silence
column4: before the shame. i lived like a ghost
column5: circling my life. it was far too painful to be tethered to a body

column1: art saved me. writing reminded me i am human and i am not alone. the creative process revealed the divine spark inside of everything. it kept me connected to my truth until the day i was finally ready to speak. books became my angels and guides. i remember reading the line from emily dickinson: ""my wars are laid away in books"" and thinking
column2: ""yes. my secret wars. and my medicine."" when i started my path to recovery
column3: i found a turquoise journal i wrote in when i was 10. on the first page i inscribed this: ""i aspire to one day be a professional writer."" i wanted to live in a world where my voice was valued.

column1: i write for that little girl and all who need to be reminded of their worth. today i want to share this: no matter how this world has broken your heart or how many losses you've faced
column2: no matter what you had to do to survive or how many ways people have lied about who you truly are
column3: you are *unconditionally* valuable. wherever you have felt most cut off from love
column4: may decadent  love be revealed in that place.

column2: so you can take a look. üî•

column1: just a quick update over the last few months: long months of travels which i'll start sharing here soon. also revisiting tibetan exiled colonies
column2: an ethnic community i have closely aligned myself with since almost a decade. it's been hard to come to terms with a refugee community that is self-destructing itself & letting go of their core cause & identity. i'm soon travelling to one of the most influential & spiritual abode that ties the tibetan people together

column12: & several of my outpouring of personal stories of abuse & survival through #metoo...it's been a strangely compelling & powerful journey for me.

column1: 227731;instagram;2018-11-14 18:29:14;FALSE;"""i was a victim of domestic violence. it was at the hands of a person who i thought would never hurt me. at first i thought i would never have to worry about anything with him
column2: but truth is i was blinded by love.
i would always make up excuses for him
column3: never thinking about what i was putting my children through. all i knew was that i was married
column4: and i thought a wife was supposed to stay with her husband no matter what

column1: i tried and tried. at times my family wouldn't see me for days because i was hiding my face from them.

there were nights when i would ball up in a knot while everyone else was asleep and cry to myself. there were also times after he would beat me when he'd tell me he'd kill me if i left him. some nights while he was sleeping
column2: i would even think about ways to kill him before he killed me. but then i came to reality and figured that if i was having those types of thoughts
column3: then it was clearly time for me to go. .

column1: so if you're reading this and you're going though something like this
column2: it's not worth it to stay because it's only gonna get worse. stop making excuses. nobody deserves to be beat up
column3: and i know it's not always easy to leave
column4: but in the end you will be happy."" ¬© anna

column4: i shared an incredible experience with nearly 100 cast and crew at the kingston penitentiary. the pen closed in 2013 and has been open for limited tours in recent years.

column1: when director jay middaugh suggested we try and get the pen for our upcoming hold back the river video shoot
column2: i knew that meant i was going to have to actually find the courage to tour the property.  it had never interested me before.  it is a national historic site and a huge part of the history of kingston
column3: but the idea of exposing myself to the energy in those buildings on the site made me feel sick.  we had two extensive tours of the grounds and buildings before we settled on october 29th as our filming date.  when the morning of the video shoot arrived
column4: i felt different about the space.  i changed my mind on deciding to not just ""get through"" the day but to allow it to be an opportunity to bring in an abundance of positive and loving energy to a place that has been filled with negativity since it's opening in 1835.

column1: i would like to thank the entire group of brave
column2: passionate and positive human beings who committed themselves on october 29th to infiltrating new beautiful energy into a place of darkness.  some of the incredible participants shared their stories with me.  many were very personal and i am grateful they felt that this experience was an opportunity to do some healing and to gather as a group of women passionate about an important movement.

column1: the first step to fixing a problem is recognizing there's a problem.
the truth will set us free.

column1: 227905;instagram;2018-11-14 15:48:38;FALSE;"wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014
column2: when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

column1: documents show the john bolton super pac
column2: which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton
column4: 700 in 2014 for ""behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging."" those services included strategies that broke individual voters into ""clusters"" based on what messages would resonate with them.

column1: wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign
column2: such as ""drain the swamp"" and imagery of walls. ""a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014

column1: he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. ""everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval
column3: who left the company in late 2014.

column2: there is no one method or formula for determining reparations.

column1: so much of the violence we experience is personalized. the violence we experience as individuals is always shared by other people and communities
column2: yet how it affects us is embodied and related to who we are in this earth walk. that's why this method was designed for people like you and #metoo.
calculating reparations is always an economic and spiritual practice.
the spiritual dimension of this method is central
column3: and #survivors must lead each initiative. the point is to #foster #healing

column2: so much had changed since the first time we did the trail after the 2016 election. i spent time in paris without the negative soundtrack that was rotting my brain and confidence here in the states
column5: and i left a six-figure salary to join a startup only to leave the startup 95 days later without a backup plan. this time
column6: i had nothing in my way except myself and my old stories. i had been playing with this concept of #hikingmyfeelings and was excited to work through some stuff on the trail.

column1: i knew this trip was going to be a big deal just by deciding to attempt the trail again. i knew the timing was divinely guided and i wanted to capture every moment. i recorded a long entry before we even left for the trail
column2: and then did one at every major milestone during the 40+ mile journey across the island.

column1: the first hike was the start of my journey to love my body. before setting foot in that @rei dressing room in december 2016
column2: i had done my research on the trail and had an idea of what to expect. with one simple question
column3: ""how did we get here?"" and a gentle nudge
column4: ""how can we honor our inner athlete?"" i had no idea what kind of adventure i was about to embark on.
